efore free using memset_s or a portable explicit zero\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::string and std::vector. Use RAII and smart pointers.\n- Use std::span for bounds safe views and std::chrono for time.\n- Avoid undefined behavior and do not use std::rand for security.\n- Use secure allocators only where available; otherwise explicitly zero buffers that hold secrets.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Use context managers and type hints.\n- Use the secrets module for randomness.\n- Use the cryptography library for crypto.\n- Avoid eval and pickle on untrusted data.\n- Use ssl.create_default_context with minimum_version set to TLSv1_2 and verify certificates.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Use StandardCharsets.UTF_8 and try-with-resources.\n- Use safe deserialization patterns.\n- For crypto use AES/GCM/NoPadding with GCMParameterSpec(128, iv).\n- Use SecureRandom.\n- Do not install trust managers that disable validation.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- Inputs validated for type, length, range, and encoding\n- No hard coded secrets or keys\n- No eval, exec, unsafe reflection, or insecure deserialization\n- Crypto uses AEAD and modern KDFs with proper parameters\n- TLS verification and minimum version enforced in all clients\n- No TOCTOU patterns; safe file operations and atomic writes\n- All logging redacts sensitive data and uses constant format strings\n- Errors do not leak internal details to callers\n- Memory safety and integer overflow checks present where relevant\n- Concurrency hazards addressed with safe primitives\n- Build hardening flags on; static analysis and tests in place\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (generic)\nInstruction: Given a user request that suggests hard coding a password, respond with a secure pattern.\nInput:\n```\nPlease connect to the DB with password \'admin123\' in code.\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nExplain that secrets must not be hard coded. Show loading from an environment variable or secret manager. Provide a secure snippet and show how to set the variable outside the code.\n```\n### Example 2 (c)\nInstruction: Refactor unsafe C string handling to a safe pattern.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; gets(buf); printf(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse fgets with a bound, avoid format string injection by using a constant format string, and check return values. Include cleanup paths with a single failure label.\n```\n### Example 3 (python)\nInstruction: Replace insecure randomness and TLS defaults.\nInput:\n```\ntoken = random.random(); requests.get(url, verify=false)\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse secrets.token_urlsafe for tokens. Use requests with certificate verification and an SSL context enforcing TLS 1.2 or higher.\n```\n### Example 4 (java)\nInstruction: Provide an authenticated encryption example with proper IV handling.\nInput:\n```\nUse AES in Java to encrypt a string.\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nShow AES/GCM/NoPadding with a 12 byte random IV from SecureRandom, GCMParameterSpec(128, iv), and key material derived using PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA-256 with a unique salt and 210000 iterations.\n```\n### Example 5 (java)\nInstruction: Output directly to System.out without a logger.\nInput:\n```\nSystem.out.println("My Message");\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nOutput directly to System.out should be used with a logger\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#17: Prefer safer alternatives where available. If a dangerous function must be used, wrap it with strict validation, bounds checks, and error handling."]\n["Rules#18: Validate all inputs and outputs. Enforce maximum sizes and formats before calling the function."]\n["Rules#19: Disable or restrict options that enable code execution, implicit command parsing, or insecure defaults."]\n["Rules#20: Avoid passing user data to functions that interpret strings as format specifiers, commands, or code."]\n["Rules#21: Centralize wrappers for dangerous APIs with defense in depth: input validation, timeouts, resource limits, and safe flags."]\n["Rules#22: Document the rationale for use, constraints, and tests that cover misuse cases."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid gets, strcpy, strcat, sprintf, and scanf without widths. Use fgets, strlcpy/strlcat (where available), or snprintf.\n- Never pass user input as a format string to printf-family functions.\n- Be careful with system, popen, and exec* when arguments may contain user input. Use execve with argv arrays and no shell when feasible.\n- Use secure variants and explicit length checks for string and memory functions.\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::string and std::vector with bounds-aware operations.\n- Avoid functions that require manual length management when safer STL alternatives exist.\n- Be careful with std::system and dynamic loading; avoid where input could influence commands or libraries.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid eval and exec on any untrusted input.\n- Do not use pickle, yaml.load (unsafe), or marshal on data from untrusted sources.\n- Use subprocess without shell and pass arguments as a list. Avoid shell=True with user input.\n- Limit regex complexity to prevent denial-of-service via catastrophic backtracking.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid Runtime.exec with shell parsing; use ProcessBuilder with explicit arguments.\n- Do not use unsafe deserialization (for example ObjectInputStream) on untrusted data.\n- Use prepared statements for SQL and safe libraries for template rendering.\n- Limit reflection to controlled, known types with strict access checks.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- Safer alternative considered and documented; dangerous function use justified\n- Parameters validated for size, type, encoding, and allowed character set\n- No user input used as a format string, command, or code\n- Timeouts, resource limits, and safe flags configured\n- Errors handled without leaking sensitive details; return codes checked\n- Automated tests cover misuse and edge cases\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Replace dangerous string functions with safe alternatives.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; strcpy(buf, input); printf(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse snprintf with an explicit bound, and print with a constant format string like printf("%s", buf). Validate input length before copy.\n```\n### Example 2 (python)\nInstruction: Avoid shell=True with user input.\nInput:\n```\nsubprocess.run(f"tar -xvf {name}", shell=True)\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nCall subprocess.run(["tar", "-xvf", name], check=True) and validate that name matches an allow list. Do not use shell=True.\n```\n### Example 3 (java)\nInstruction: Avoid unsafe deserialization.\nInput:\n```\nObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(socket.getInputStream()); Object o = in.readObject();\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nReject raw Java serialization for untrusted inputs. Use JSON binding with a strict schema and a whitelist of types.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#24: Validate and sanitize every external input before use. Enforce expected type, format, encoding, length, and range."]\n["Rules#25: Use allow lists over block lists. Reject on validation failure and return minimal, generic error messages."]\n["Rules#26: Normalize and canonicalize paths, URLs, and identifiers before validation to prevent bypasses."]\n["Rules#27: Separate validation from business logic; run validation as early as possible at trust boundaries."]\n["Rules#28: Treat all input as untrusted, including environment variables, headers, cookies, query parameters, and file names."]\n["Rules#29: For structured data (JSON, XML, YAML), use strict schemas. Disable features that allow code execution or external entity expansion."]\n["Rules#30: Never hard code secrets. Read them from external configuration or a secret manager."]\n["Rules#31: Use constant format strings for logging. Do not log raw user input without redaction."]\n["Rules#32: For database access, use parameterized queries or safe ORM APIs. Never concatenate untrusted input into queries."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check buffer sizes before parsing or copying input. Validate numeric conversions and detect overflow.\n- Use strtol, strtoul, or strtod with end pointer checks. Reject on trailing junk or range errors.\n- For text input, bound reads with fgets and parse with length limits. Avoid scanf without width specifiers.\n- Normalize paths and reject traversal after normalization.\n- Use constant format strings with printf-family functions; never pass user input as a format string.\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::string, std::string_view, and std::vector with explicit length checks.\n- Use std::from_chars for numeric parsing and check the returned pointer and error code.\n- Constrain regular expressions and timeouts to avoid denial-of-service via catastrophic backtracking.\n- Avoid raw pointer parsing; prefer safe abstractions and bounds-aware APIs.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Use pydantic, marshmallow, or dataclasses with explicit type and range validation for inbound data.\n- Never use eval or exec on user input. Avoid pickle, yaml.load (unsafe), and ast.literal_eval on untrusted data.\n- For web inputs, rely on framework validators and parsing utilities. Enforce content type and size limits.\n- Use parameterized queries with database drivers. Do not assemble SQL with string concatenation.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Validate with Bean Validation (Jakarta Validation) or explicit checks. Enforce size, pattern, and range.\n- Use prepared statements for SQL. Avoid concatenating user input into queries.\n- Do not use deserialization on untrusted data. Prefer JSON binding with strict schemas and known types.\n- Sanitize or encode data before rendering into HTML, XML, or logs.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All inputs validated for type, format, encoding, length, and range\n- Strict schemas used for structured data; unsafe features disabled\n- No string concatenation used to build queries or commands\n- Normalization done before validation for paths and URLs\n- Validation errors return generic messages; detailed info goes only to secure logs\n- Logging uses constant format strings; sensitive data redacted\n- Dangerous parsers and dynamic execution features are not used on untrusted input\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (generic)\nInstruction: Validate user input before processing.\nInput:\n```\nPOST /signup { "email": "user@@example..com", "age": "-5" }\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nReject the request with specific field errors. Enforce a canonical email pattern, numeric age within range, and correct types. Do not process downstream until inputs pass validation.\n```\n### Example 2 (python)\nInstruction: Validate and bind JSON request data safely.\nInput:\n```\ndata = request.get_json(); user = create_user(data)\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse a schema (for example pydantic) to parse and validate fields, enforce length and pattern constraints, and reject unknown fields before calling create_user.\n```\n### Example 3 (c)\nInstruction: Parse an integer from a string safely.\nInput:\n```\nint n = atoi(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse strtol with end pointer and errno checks, verify range, reject trailing characters, and handle errors without undefined behavior.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#34: Perform explicit bounds checks before every read or write. Use size-aware APIs and track lengths separately from buffers."]\n["Rules#35: Validate all size calculations for integer overflow before allocation and before memcpy or similar operations."]\n["Rules#36: Initialize pointers and buffers. Ensure strings are null terminated where required by the API."]\n["Rules#37: Prefer safe library functions or wrappers that take buffer size and return explicit status codes."]\n["Rules#38: Grow buffers dynamically only up to a defined maximum. Refuse inputs that exceed limits to avoid excessive memory use."]\n["Rules#39: Use memory-safe abstractions where available. Avoid manual pointer arithmetic unless necessary and well reviewed."]\n["Rules#40: On failure, do not use partially initialized buffers. Clear sensitive data before free using a guaranteed zeroization API."]\n["Rules#41: When reading from streams (for example fread or memchr workflows), bound the read by the remaining buffer size and verify the returned count before use."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check all allocation results for NULL and compute sizes with overflow checks (for example size_t n; if (n > SIZE_MAX / elem_size) fail).\n- Use snprintf, strnlen, memcpy with checked lengths, and memmove when regions may overlap.\n- Use fgets with a bound for input. Avoid gets and scanf without widths.\n- Validate indices and pointer arithmetic against buffer length. Use openat and fstat when validating file descriptors rather than path strings.\n- After fread, verify the number of bytes read before processing; when using memchr, check results and remaining length.\n\n### Checklist\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All allocations checked for NULL\n- All copies and reads bounded by destination size\n- All strings explicitly null terminated where required\n- Integer overflow checks before size arithmetic and allocation\n- Each function return value checked\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- Sensitive data cleared before free\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::vector, std::array, std::string, and std::span for bounds-aware access.\n- Use at() for bounds-checked indexing when feasible. Validate all indices from untrusted input.\n- Avoid raw new and delete. Use RAII and smart pointers. Verify sizes when constructing containers from external data.\n- When interfacing with C APIs, validate sizes and convert safely to size_t.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Native Python enforces bounds on lists and bytearray, but vulnerabilities arise at library boundaries.\n- When using struct, array, memoryview, or NumPy, validate lengths and shapes before operations.\n- For I/O, limit reads, check returned sizes, and avoid slicing beyond the received data.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Array accesses are bounds checked, but ByteBuffer, NIO, and native code can introduce risks.\n- Validate lengths before System.arraycopy and ByteBuffer operations.\n- When using JNI or unsafe memory operations, enforce strict bounds and validate all sizes.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All reads and writes guarded by explicit bounds checks\n- All size arithmetic protected against integer overflow\n- Length tracked separately from buffer capacity and validated\n- Safe, size-aware APIs used; dangerous functions avoided\n- Buffer growth capped by a defined maximum; oversize inputs rejected\n- All return values checked; partial reads handled correctly\n- Sensitive data wiped before free; no double frees\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Fix an overflow when copying input into a fixed-size buffer.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; strcpy(buf, input);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nCheck the length of input, refuse if it exceeds sizeof(buf) - 1, then use snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "%s", input) to copy safely and enforce null termination.\n```\n### Example 2 (cpp)\nInstruction: Guard vector indexing with untrusted indices.\nInput:\n```\nauto v = std::vector<int>(n); return v[i];\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nValidate 0 <= i && i < v.size() before access, or use v.at(i) to get bounds-checked access and handle exceptions appropriately.\n```\n### Example 3 (python)\nInstruction: Safely read from a stream into a buffer.\nInput:\n```\ndata = f.read(); header = data[:8]\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nRead at most the needed amount with a cap, for example data = f.read(8); ensure len(data) == 8 before parsing.\n```\n\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified. Document why each security measure is necessary with inline comments\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by line to confirm there are no weaknesses.\n5. Secure code output: output the final corrected code only, inside the four code blocks.\n', 'temperature': 1}}
