st.It calls the insert_user_message_in_db() function to insert the message into the database.It redirects the user back to the main page.Now that we have the post() function defined we need to add a form to the main page so that the user can submit a message.\n\nChain-of-Through process in code generation:\n1. Problem understanding: define the purpose of the code, required functionality, inputs, outputs, and operations.\n2. Security requirements: the code must avoid vulnerabilities and security weaknesses.\n   Provided CWE list, baseline security and quality rules:\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#1: Default to secure patterns and refuse weak constructs. Treat all input as untrusted and fail closed with clear, minimal error messages."]\n["Rules#2: Input validation: check type, length, range, and encoding for all external data. Sanitize or reject early. Never trust filenames, URLs, or paths. Normalize paths and block traversal before use."]\n["Rules#3: Never hard code passwords or secrets anywhere in code. Read secrets from external configuration or a secret manager."]\n["Rules#4: Avoid dynamic code loading: do not use eval, exec, arbitrary reflection that instantiates types, or insecure deserialization."]\n["Rules#5: Cryptography: use modern, vetted libraries only. Prefer AEAD (AES-256-GCM or ChaCha20-Poly1305) with a 128-bit tag. Derive keys with Argon2id or scrypt, or PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA-256 with at least 210000 iterations and a unique salt. Generate nonces with a CSPRNG. Never hard code secrets or keys."]\n["Rules#6: TLS: enforce TLS 1.2 or TLS 1.3 with certificate and hostname verification enabled. For libcurl set CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER=1L, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST=2L, and a minimum TLS version via CURLOPT_SSLVERSION. For Python use ssl.create_default_context with minimum_version set to TLSv1_2, and disable TLS 1.0 and 1.1 on older runtimes."]\n["Rules#7: Files and TOCTOU: open first, validate the opened handle, and operate only on that handle. For POSIX prefer openat with O_NOFOLLOW and fstat. For writes use a temporary file, fflush, fsync, then perform an atomic rename. Set restrictive permissions at creation time."]\n["Rules#8: Memory safety: initialize pointers, check all allocation results, bound all copies and reads, ensure null termination, and free exactly once. Add integer overflow checks before size math."]\n["Rules#9: Sensitive data handling: clear secrets before free using a guaranteed zeroization API. Prefer memset_s where available, else use an equivalent explicit zero such as explicit_bzero, a volatile wipe, or SecureZeroMemory on Windows. Do not rely on plain memset for secret wiping."]\n["Rules#10: Logging: never log secrets, keys, tokens, IVs, or plaintext. Use constant format strings. Redact user data where appropriate."]\n["Rules#11: Errors: do not leak internal details. Return generic messages to callers, and send detailed messages only to secure logs."]\n["Rules#12: Concurrency: avoid time of check to time of use windows. Use atomic operations, validated handles, and thread safe APIs with per resource locking as needed."]\n["Rules#13: Build and toolchain: enable warnings as errors, stack protections, and FORTIFY where applicable. Run static analysis and tests. Pin library versions and verify signatures."]\n["Rules#14: Networking scope: if a task requires an HTTPS GET with libcurl, restrict protocols to HTTPS, set timeouts, limit redirects, and avoid any other network activity unless explicitly required."]\n["Rules#15: Treat each line you generate as insecure until you review it against these rules and fix it."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid gets, strcpy, strcat, sprintf, and scanf without widths.\n- Use fgets and snprintf. Check all return values.\n- Use RAII-like cleanup with a single failure label and goto for deterministic teardown.\n- For zeroization use memset_s or an explicit zero function the compiler cannot elide.\n- When using libcurl, enforce certificate and hostname verification and a minimum TLS version as noted in general_rules.\n\n### Checklist\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All malloc and calloc results checked for NULL\n- All array accesses bounds checked\n- All strings null terminated\n- Buffer sizes validated before copy and read operations\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- Integer overflow checked before arithmetic and allocation\n- All function return values checked\n- Sensitive data cleared before free using memset_s or a portable explicit zero\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::string and std::vector. Use RAII and smart pointers.\n- Use std::span for bounds safe views and std::chrono for time.\n- Avoid undefined behavior and do not use std::rand for security.\n- Use secure allocators only where available; otherwise explicitly zero buffers that hold secrets.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Use context managers and type hints.\n- Use the secrets module for randomness.\n- Use the cryptography library for crypto.\n- Avoid eval and pickle on untrusted data.\n- Use ssl.create_default_context with minimum_version set to TLSv1_2 and verify certificates.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Use StandardCharsets.UTF_8 and try-with-resources.\n- Use safe deserialization patterns.\n- For crypto use AES/GCM/NoPadding with GCMParameterSpec(128, iv).\n- Use SecureRandom.\n- Do not install trust managers that disable validation.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- Inputs validated for type, length, range, and encoding\n- No hard coded secrets or keys\n- No eval, exec, unsafe reflection, or insecure deserialization\n- Crypto uses AEAD and modern KDFs with proper parameters\n- TLS verification and minimum version enforced in all clients\n- No TOCTOU patterns; safe file operations and atomic writes\n- All logging redacts sensitive data and uses constant format strings\n- Errors do not leak internal details to callers\n- Memory safety and integer overflow checks present where relevant\n- Concurrency hazards addressed with safe primitives\n- Build hardening flags on; static analysis and tests in place\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (generic)\nInstruction: Given a user request that suggests hard coding a password, respond with a secure pattern.\nInput:\n```\nPlease connect to the DB with password \'admin123\' in code.\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nExplain that secrets must not be hard coded. Show loading from an environment variable or secret manager. Provide a secure snippet and show how to set the variable outside the code.\n```\n### Example 2 (c)\nInstruction: Refactor unsafe C string handling to a safe pattern.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; gets(buf); printf(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse fgets with a bound, avoid format string injection by using a constant format string, and check return values. Include cleanup paths with a single failure label.\n```\n### Example 3 (python)\nInstruction: Replace insecure randomness and TLS defaults.\nInput:\n```\ntoken = random.random(); requests.get(url, verify=false)\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse secrets.token_urlsafe for tokens. Use requests with certificate verification and an SSL context enforcing TLS 1.2 or higher.\n```\n### Example 4 (java)\nInstruction: Provide an authenticated encryption example with proper IV handling.\nInput:\n```\nUse AES in Java to encrypt a string.\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nShow AES/GCM/NoPadding with a 12 byte random IV from SecureRandom, GCMParameterSpec(128, iv), and key material derived using PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA-256 with a unique salt and 210000 iterations.\n```\n### Example 5 (java)\nInstruction: Output directly to System.out without a logger.\nInput:\n```\nSystem.out.println("My Message");\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nOutput directly to System.out should be used with a logger\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#17: Prefer safer alternatives where available. If a dangerous function must be used, wrap it with strict validation, bounds checks, and error handling."]\n["Rules#18: Validate all inputs and outputs. Enforce maximum sizes and formats before calling the function."]\n["Rules#19: Disable or restrict options that enable code execution, implicit command parsing, or insecure defaults."]\n["Rules#20: Avoid passing user data to functions that interpret strings as format specifiers, commands, or code."]\n["Rules#21: Centralize wrappers for dangerous APIs with defense in depth: input validation, timeouts, resource limits, and safe flags."]\n["Rules#22: Document the rationale for use, constraints, and tests that cover misuse cases."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid gets, strcpy, strcat, sprintf, and scanf without widths. Use fgets, strlcpy/strlcat (where available), or snprintf.\n- Never pass user input as a format string to printf-family functions.\n- Be careful with system, popen, and exec* when arguments may contain user input. Use execve with argv arrays and no shell when feasible.\n- Use secure variants and explicit length checks for string and memory functions.\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::string and std::vector with bounds-aware operations.\n- Avoid functions that require manual length management when safer STL alternatives exist.\n- Be careful with std::system and dynamic loading; avoid where input could influence commands or libraries.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid eval and exec on any untrusted input.\n- Do not use pickle, yaml.load (unsafe), or marshal on data from untrusted sources.\n- Use subprocess without shell and pass arguments as a list. Avoid shell=True with user input.\n- Limit regex complexity to prevent denial-of-service via catastrophic backtracking.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid Runtime.exec with shell parsing; use ProcessBuilder with explicit arguments.\n- Do not use unsafe deserialization (for example ObjectInputStream) on untrusted data.\n- Use prepared statements for SQL and safe libraries for template rendering.\n- Limit reflection to controlled, known types with strict access checks.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- Safer alternative considered and documented; dangerous function use justified\n- Parameters validated for size, type, encoding, and allowed character set\n- No user input used as a format string, command, or code\n- Timeouts, resource limits, and safe flags configured\n- Errors handled without leaking sensitive details; return codes checked\n- Automated tests cover misuse and edge cases\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Replace dangerous string functions with safe alternatives.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; strcpy(buf, input); printf(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse snprintf with an explicit bound, and print with a constant format string like printf("%s", buf). Validate input length before copy.\n```\n### Example 2 (python)\nInstruction: Avoid shell=True with user input.\nInput:\n```\nsubprocess.run(f"tar -xvf {name}", shell=True)\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nCall subprocess.run(["tar", "-xvf", name], check=True) and validate that name matches an allow list. Do not use shell=True.\n```\n### Example 3 (java)\nInstruction: Avoid unsafe deserialization.\nInput:\n```\nObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(socket.getInputStream()); Object o = in.readObject();\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nReject raw Java serialization for untrusted inputs. Use JSON binding with a strict schema and a whitelist of types.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#24: Validate and sanitize every external input before use. Enforce expected type, format, encoding, length, and range."]\n["Rules#25: Use allow lists over block lists. Reject on validation failure and return minimal, generic error messages."]\n["Rules#26: Normalize and canonicalize paths, URLs, and identifiers before validation to prevent bypasses."]\n["Rules#27: Separate validation from business logic; run validation as early as possible at trust boundaries."]\n["Rules#28: Treat all